Mei's Stage
London — The newly appointed British Prime Minister Theresa May faces a daunting task: carrying out the demand of the British people — or more accurately, the voters of England and Wales — to leave the European Union and managing the far-reaching consequences of this undertaking.
The challenge she faces dwarfs that of all her predecessors in recent years.
But she may have the ability to complete this task.
No one should underestimate Mei.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has already demonstrated courage in a series of crises, May has all the tools necessary to accomplish the task in her hands.
She is intelligent and resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not bound by any ideology, is very skilled at taking control, and operates within self-imposed boundaries to ensure familiarity with the issues she handles.
Mei won most of the battles she participated in and showed no mercy to those who had treated her unfairly.
However, she has made few enemies within the party and is quite popular among ordinary members.
This is a powerful combination — she needs to make full use of it to lead the Brexit process in the UK.
There is no doubt that the Brexit process has already begun.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum could not be reversed.
She repeatedly stated, "Brexit means Brexit," and her ministers also supported her view.
But May has not yet given a precise definition of Brexit.
This task is extremely difficult to complete.
Imagine someone saying to you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starting to prepare food for you.
It's hard to clearly know what you're actually going to eat.
A Northern Irish "Ulster Fry"—eggs, bacon, sausage, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes—with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you may have very different feelings about various possible combinations.
The same applies to Brexit.
Some people may primarily focus on preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Others are more concerned about gaining access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, the UK cannot order a full portion of every dish listed on the menu.
A reality often overlooked by the Brexit camp is that the EU does not give benefits to the UK for free.
This is not because the EU leaders want to win popularity or because they are punishing the UK for rejecting the EU (such inflammatory rhetoric sometimes gains momentum, for example, when Boris Johnson, the UK's new Foreign Secretary, referred to it as "Hitler-style imperialism").
On the contrary, we British often forget that everyone—including the EU and all its member states—has political or commercial interests they are committed to protecting.
For May, the central challenge over the next few months will be to determine what Britain's objectives should be, based on reality, in its relationship with the European Union (and with the world in the area of trade) after the difficult negotiations have begun.
Given the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six major topics that would require separate negotiations), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(When the negotiations are completed, my granddaughter, who is now 11 years old, might already be starting college!)
We must clarify our priorities to prevent the negotiations from dragging on longer.
The obvious goal is to strike a balance between allowing goods and services (particularly financial services) exported from the UK to enter other European countries and restricting the movement of EU citizens into the UK.
The more a negotiator gains in one area, the greater the concessions they need to make in other areas.
Mei needs to make full use of her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her goal, she will still find that the discontented are not just a part of them — such a result is inevitable — but all of them.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing the May government: narrowing the growing divide in British society exposed by Brexit.
The blue-collar workers in northern and central England were the main driving force behind the Brexit referendum. They have long been alienated from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called globalizing agent—the European Union.
The metropolitan areas of England — particularly London — may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have not reaped any of the rewards.
Many members of the blue-collar working class ultimately fell prey to the promises of anti-establishment figures due to a lack of confidence in the Labour Party led by left-wing leader Jeremy Corbyn.
"They said, 'We will reverse globalization.'"
"We will drive out immigrants who depress wages and redirect hundreds of millions of pounds originally paid to the EU into public services."
They promised that Brexit would allow the UK to relive a safer and more prosperous past.
Leave supporters cannot truly deliver on these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, and similarly, immigration from the EU cannot be cut off.
Any such measures would only destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturns lead to a decrease in immigration, workers who voted for Brexit may still find themselves disillusioned, as low-paying jobs remain low-paying and the pressure on public services remains heavy.
This is unlikely to significantly enhance social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has unleashed a storm of uncontrollable populist sentiment.
Just as Donald Trump has been unable to improve the situation of working-class American voters, regardless of how things may appear, Brexit has also failed to deliver any benefits to those who chose it.
Although it has many advantages, such challenges may still be beyond Mei's ability to overcome.
